<h2 class="nhsuk-heading-l">1. About the programme</h2>
<p class="nhsuk-body">
  People with sickle cell disease do not reliably receive timely analgesia during acute painful
  episodes in the NHS, and too often experience poor care. The Observatory’s 2022–23 discovery
  research with University Hospitals Bristol and Weston found that personalised digital care plans
  show real promise for improving access to, experience of, and accountability of care — but have
  not been widely tested or adopted. This programme commissions the build of that service and
  pilots it through an NHS partner. See <a class="nhsuk-link" href="{{ '/case/' | url }}">the case</a>
  and <a class="nhsuk-link" href="{{ '/service/' | url }}">what we’re building</a>.
</p>

<h2 class="nhsuk-heading-l">2. What we are asking you to build</h2>
<p class="nhsuk-body">A production-grade digital service that lets authorised users create, hold,
update and view a personalised sickle cell care plan, with the acute crisis view at its heart.
Core capabilities include:</p>
<ul class="nhsuk-list nhsuk-list--bullet">
  <li>Role-based access for <strong>healthcare professionals, patients, and nominated delegates</strong> (e.g. next of kin).</li>
  <li>A structured care plan and an at-a-glance, printable <strong>acute crisis view</strong> (analgesia and opioid tolerance, allergies and adverse reactions, baseline observations, escalation, named consultant, pregnancy flag, emergency contacts).</li>
  <li>Document upload and viewing alongside the structured plan.</li>
  <li>Research consent capture, an episode Friends &amp; Family Test, and free-text feedback.</li>
  <li>A full audit trail and a <strong>patient-facing access log</strong> — accountability and transparency built into the product.</li>
  <li>Availability to authorised users wherever care is delivered, including non-specialist settings.</li>
</ul>
<p class="nhsuk-body">
  A working <strong>prototype</strong> and a detailed requirements set already exist and are open
  source. We expect you to build on the learning — not necessarily the code — to deliver a robust,
  assured service. Explore it in the
  <a class="nhsuk-link" href="{{ site.repoUrl }}">project repository</a>.
</p>

<h2 class="nhsuk-heading-l">3. Assurance and technical requirements</h2>
<p class="nhsuk-body">The production service must meet NHS and public-sector standards, including:</p>
<ul class="nhsuk-list nhsuk-list--bullet">
  <li><strong>Identity:</strong> NHS Care Identity (CIS2) sign-in for clinicians; assured, proportionate identity for patients and delegates.</li>
  <li><strong>Information governance:</strong> Data Protection Impact Assessment, data protection by design, and compliance with UK GDPR and NHS data security standards (DSPT).</li>
  <li><strong>Clinical safety:</strong> DCB0129 / DCB0160 clinical risk management, with a named Clinical Safety Officer.</li>
  <li><strong>Accessibility:</strong> WCAG 2.2 AA, meeting the public sector accessibility regulations, evidenced by audit.</li>
  <li><strong>Hosting &amp; security:</strong> NHS-approved cloud hosting, penetration testing, and antivirus-scanned uploads.</li>
  <li><strong>Standards alignment:</strong> the <a class="nhsuk-link" href="https://service-manual.nhs.uk/standards-and-technology/service-standard">NHS service standard</a> and the NHS design system.</li>
  <li><strong>Interoperability:</strong> a clear path toward integration with clinical systems and, where appropriate, 111/999 and the shared care record.</li>
</ul>

<h2 class="nhsuk-heading-l">4. How we work</h2>
<ul class="nhsuk-list nhsuk-list--bullet">
  <li><strong>User-centred and agile</strong> — iterative delivery in discovery/alpha/beta phases, evidenced by user research.</li>
  <li><strong>Co-production</strong> — meaningful, paid involvement of people with sickle cell, families, and haematology and emergency care clinicians.</li>
  <li><strong>In the open</strong> — open-source code, open decisions, and outputs licensed for maximum adoption.</li>
  <li><strong>At pace</strong> — mainstream, modern delivery approaches that work well outside the NHS.</li>
</ul>

